      "is not equal to `S` unless `φ` preserves the integral lattice. \n\nBut in the Lean formalization, `φ` is arbitrary, and the claim that it preserves the integral lattice is false in general. \n\nTherefore, the `hφ` statement is actually false in general, and we cannot prove it without additional assumptions on `φ`. \n\nBut this means that the original strategy is incorrect, and the proof cannot proceed as given. \n\nBut is there an alternative? \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we do not need `hφ`, and we can directly show that `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is an `AddEquiv`, and use `MeasureTheory.addEquivAddHaarChar_congr`.\n\nBut `Aux.prodLocalComponents` maps `(...) × (Π' v, ...) → (...) × (Π' v, ...)`, and it is an `AddEquiv` because it is built from `φ : V ≃ₗ[ℚ] V`, so each component is an `AddEquiv` (and products of `AddEquiv`s are `AddEquiv`s).\n\nBut perhaps in Lean, we cannot directly use `MeasureTheory.addEquivAddHaarChar_congr`, because it requires an `AddEquiv` from `α` to `α`, but `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is from `α` to `β` (because the second component of the product is changing from `(IntegralLattice ℤ ℚ V) ⊗ ...` to `V ⊗ ...`).\n\nBut no, wait: actually, the domain and codomain of `Aux.prodLocalComponents` are not the same, because we are tensoring `(IntegralLattice ℤ ℚ V)` with `v.adicCompletion ℚ` in the domain, and `V` with `v.adicCompletion ℚ` in the codomain. But in Lean, the `c_v_alg` is defining an equivalence between these two, so the `ContinuousAddEquiv` for each component is `(c_v V v).toContinuousAddEquiv`, which is a homeomorphism. \n\nBut perhaps to avoid the problem of `hφ`, we should instead use that `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is an `AddEquiv`, because it is built from `φ : V ≃ₗ[ℚ] V`, and hence an `AddEquiv`, and then deduce that the addition character is 1 by `MeasureTheory.addEquivAddHaarChar_congr`. \n\nBut perhaps the issue is that `MeasureTheory.addEquivAddHaarChar_congr` is only for `AddEquiv α α`, but `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is `AddEquiv α β`. \n\nBut perhaps we can instead use the fact that `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is built from `φ : V ≃ₗ[ℚ] V`, so it is a homeomorphism, and then show that it preserves the addition character. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the product formula can be re-proven without `hφ`, instead directly by using the fact that for every `v`, the addition character of each component of `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is 1, and then taking the product. \n\nBut perhaps the solution is to use `MeasureTheory.addEquivAddHaarChar_congr` by showing that `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is an `AddEquiv`, even though it maps `α` to `β`? \n\nBut no, `MeasureTheory.addEquivAddHaarChar_congr` requires an `AddEquiv α α`. \n\nBut perhaps we can instead consider `AddEquiv.ofBijective`, because `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is bijective, and then manually compute the addition character. \n\nBut perhaps instead the original approach can be fixed by noting that `hφ` is actually true because `φ`, when passed through `c_v_alg`, automatically restricts to the right thing? \n\nThis is not obvious. \n\n### Actually, the confusion is deeper\n\nThe `Aux.prodLocalComponents` is not `∏' v, φ_v`, but instead is `(φ_infty) × (∏' v, φ_v)`, where:\n\n- `φ_infty : (IntegralLattice ℤ",
